<https://ostrails.github.io/assessment-component-metadata-records/metric/FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject.ttl> a ftr:Metric, dqv:Metric, dcat:Resource ;
    dcterms:identifier "https://ostrails.github.io/assessment-component-metadata-records/metric/FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject.ttl"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy "https://ostrails.github.io/assessment-component-metadata-records/metric/FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject.ttl"^^xsd:anyURI ;
    dcat:landingPage "https://ostrails.github.io/assessment-component-metadata-records/metric/FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject.ttl"^^xsd:anyURI ;
    dcterms:title "FAIR Metric – R1.3 - Metadata – use of cross-disciplinary subject vocabulary"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:label "FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject"^^xsd:string ;
    vivo:abbreviation "FM_R1.3_M_HighLevelSubject"^^xsd:string ;
    dcterms:description """### What is being measured?

This metric evaluates whether the digital object referenced by the identifier includes at least one resolvable, high-level subject term from a cross-disciplinary vocabulary (e.g., ANZSRC FOR, FAST (Faceted Application of Subject Terminology), LCSH, FAIRsharing’s SRAO). It inspects the subject or keyword fields of the metadata record to verify the presence of a URI for at least one subject tag.

### Why should we measure it?

FAIR Principle R1.3 requires metadata to follow domain-relevant community standards. While applicable to a variety of communities, the use of high-level subject vocabularies is particularly useful for institutional repositories and other generalist contexts, as it provides a standardised, cross-disciplinary schema."""^^xsd:string ;
    dcat:keyword "FAIR"^^xsd:string ;
    schema:about "Not applicable"^^xsd:string ;
    ftr:applicationArea <http://www.fairsharing.org/ontology/subject/SRAO_0000401> ;
    ftr:inDimension <https://w3id.org/fair/principles/terms/F>, <https://w3id.org/fair/principles/terms/R1.3> ;
    dcat:version "1.0.0"^^xsd:string ;
    
    dcterms:license <http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/> ;
    ftr:status "Active"@en ;
     
    
    
    
    
